r topic Prologue for story I started. It's all of the prologue in this. I edited it and added a little more.<br>
<br>
Chapter 0<br>
<br>
Evan Teadows sat in Willie's Bar and Grill and sulked. Another bad day, so he decided to get wasted. Evan was a young man, in his prime, as some would say if they looked at him. He looked fine and satisfied with his life. Of course, it was exactly the opposite inside, if it wasn't there wouldn't be much conflict inside himself. He had dark brown hair that was pushed back, mostly because he was stressed. He was skinny, stood at about 5,7, and had pale skin. His gray eyes scanned the bar and all the patrons, dark shadows were under them. He hadn't slept more than four hours in the last two days. <br>
<br>
Evan worked at a hotel for room service. Casta Del Whe' was the name, Evan had no idea what in the world it meant. They were pushing him, he had no days off that week, but thank heaven it was Monday and his first day off. He hadn't been there long, a month and a half, but he hated it. This day was especially horrible; some tubby guest spat in his face for getting the wrong wine, then left a horribly small tip. He could remember it clearly, the chubby mans' fat face in his, &quot;You better get the right champagne! I asked for Zinfandel stupid! Not Chardinay (sorry for the mispelling).&quot; Evan wanted to correct his confusion with champagne and wine but didn't.<br>
<br>
John Cook sat in the cold and dark alleyway of Earl Street. His back propped up against a dumpster. He wasn't having the best of days. He had just got pick-pocketed by a sneaky thief. It was rather ironic, a thief stealing from a homeless man. Pathetic. Anyone could tell John wasn't the richest guy in town. He wore raggedy clothes he found over time. The shirt and pants were his of course. But he found boots that were a few sizes to big for him and a trench coat left on a park bench. He also owned a aviation hat and pilot goggles from one of his grandfathers. He wasn't sure which. <br>
<br>
&quot;What to do? What to do?&quot; John tiredly asked himself in a whispering voice. He soon was lulled to sleep by his boredom. <br>
<br>
The back of Evans' head made a loud noise as hit hit the tiles on the bathroom floor. His attacker was in very strange clothing. A cloak and a hood to cover his face. <br>
That's all he noticed before he hit him. Evan was too smashed to even have a chance. The attacker bent over Evans dazed body and uttered a small sentence in his ear, &quot;Where's the disk?&quot; <br>
<br>
Several weeks before this happened to the man named Evan Teadows, Nathan Freeman sat in his car, which was parked right across the street from Willies' Bar and Grill. Never been caught, not even close. He flicked his ciggarette out the window onto the cold sidewalk and sighed. It was a full moon, about time too, Nathan liked full moons. They were one of the beautiful things in the world. Nathan was a rather small man, 5,5 and very skinny. He had dark tanned skin that was mostly covered by his dark blond hair. His hair reached down to his chin and covered most of his face just so he could see. A freak, some could say when they looked at him, but he was also a 'master' thief.  It was a cold night and he sat in his warm car with a leather trenchcoat in the passenger seat. An old fashioned cloak and hood was in the back seat. His car was an old fashioned one, black. He'd grown attached to it. Then he saw it, something he knew would get him a fortune. An armored truck rolled by across the street from him, pretty slowly. Nathan Freeman smiled and stepped out of his car.<br>
<br>
Norman Peterman couldn't move. They were treating him like a cannibal, it was insane. A police officer rolled the hand truck he was strapped to down the hallway. If it was just the straps, he could escape. But They also put him in an ugly strait jacket. Five straps that were built onto the handtruck were fastened three spots on his legs, and two on his upper body. Jeez, it wasn't like he was a disgusting cannibal, They even put a hockey mask on his face. Now he was really Jason. At least he could move his eyes, he was surprised They didn't put eye restraints since they thought he was so dangerous. Norman looked around in the holes of the hockey mask and saw more police officers and the Warden. Professor Goeman is what he wanted the prisoners to call him. Norman knew his rather embarrasing first name; Skye. It sounded rather feminine. But it wasn't time to mock him, he decided it was time to get out. &quot;Peterman, you're gettin' yer' own special room with a single cell just for you.&quot; The Warden said, as if this was exciting news.<br>
&quot;I'm jumping for joy, Skye.&quot; Goeman glared at him and Norman smiled. The cell was bigger, Norman was impressed he got a table and some pens and paper to write with. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> These people aren't too smart now, are they?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
Back at Willie's Evan was confused, &quot;Disk?&quot; He could see more clearly, the man was normal size and weight. he wore all black and talked in a hoarse voice, &quot;You know what I'm talking about. Now give it to me!&quot; Evan sat up and pressed his back against the wall, &quot;What?&quot; <br>
