Chapter One<br>
<br>
<br>
Evan felt the rumbling in his stomach, it felt awkward in his throat. He and everyone who’s ever had one too many drinks knows the feeling. He got off his barstool and dashed for the bathroom, hands over his closed mouth. The vomit was slowly coming up. He pushed the Mens’ door open and frantically looked around. He knew where the stalls were, but looking around gave the moment something, a dramatic touch. He stepped in the middle stall and closed the door and locked it behind him. Then he got on his knees, bent his head over the toilet bowl and closed his eyes. The vomit forcefully came out, Evan didn’t make much noise but the puke splashing everywhere in the bowl did. It stopped, a string of gooey saliva hung from his mouth, he could smell the mix of puke and beer. Evan heard the bathroom door open and close and footsteps. He quickly wiped his mouth as the footsteps stopped and unlocked the stall door. The person who just walked in was the attacker. Evan now sat against the wall of the bathroom, a slight patch of blood on the back of his head, and bad breath. The man didn’t take money or anything, he just wanted a disk… Whatever, Evan decided he should leave after absolutely no reconsidering.<br>
<br>
Nathan Freeman was happy with what he did, he was satisfied. To him, satisfaction was the treasure in life. Theivery was his key to the treasure. Whatever was in the armored car ahead of Nathans’ a few weeks before now was sure to be satisfying. The armored car turned left a block ahead of where Nathan was first parked. Nathan followed suit. He didn’t want the people in the car to be too suspicious so when they took a right he went straight. He would meet up with the car up the road, if they didn’t turn before that. Nathan took the next right and waited at the end of the street, he saw the car coming his way, excellent. So good so far. Nathan played this little game until the armored car slowed in front of a rather big building. Cashman Bank, Nathan had only been here once before. It was one of his bank robbery jobs, since he was a novice he was nervous and only got a few hundreds. He parked his car a little ways down the street and grabbed his cloak and hood from the backseat. He also grabbed a combat knife in a holder and clipped it on his belt.<br>
<br>
John Cook was awakened by something that landed in his lap. His neck was sore, as usual, his eyes slowly and heavily opened. He glanced around the alley dazed, and looked into his lap. “Woah!” This really put the term, ‘lap of luxury’ into good use. In Johns’ lap was a bundle of money, strapped together with a rubber band. He gawked at the prize, it must has been half a foot thick. Someone had to have dropped it from the roof, he looked up but saw nobody. Then he shakily picked the bundle up and fingered through it, They were all tens. But at the end was a small piece of paper that read, ‘For more, come to the library steps, now.’<br>
<br>
The delicate hand that held the pen lazily drifted across the big pad of paper. Norman Peterman kept his face to the drawing, but his eyes darted everywhere. To the cot, which had thick and hot gray blankets, then to the camera, which was out of the cell, watching him. &lt;i&gt;Thank heavens for long sleeves.&lt;/i&gt; He finished up the drawing, it was a mountain, and lifted his arm to put the pen in the holder. His hand bumped the holder making it fall off the desk. Norman quickly got up and walked around the desk to the opposite side, then bent down, back facing the cameras’ steady gaze, to pick them up. Norman put all of the pens but one back in the holder, with this one he pushed it up his sleeve far enough so it was out of sight. Norman looked at the clock on the wall opposite of the cell and saw it was late. He set the penholder upon the desk and got under the covers of his cot.<br>
<br>
At the same time Nathan was planning this armored car robbery, Sam Biggins sat in the passenger seat of the family car. A white jeep, several years old, Sam felt most comfortable in the passenger seat in the front. His parents were inside the hotel, checking out. Sam was eleven, turning twelve tomorrow, he was rather small for his age. He weighed sixty-five pounds, he didn’t know how short he was, shorter than everyone in his class was, he knew. It was the second week of summer vacation. Sam drew a picture of a mountain, or at least tried, you couldn’t blame him for giving it the old college try. <br>
<br>
John walked along Crescent Road with a slight charming look on his face. He couldn’t wait to get more, that was how Greed did its job, but he had to wonder if it was some sort of trick. He turned left and saw the library steps ahead. This was twenty minutes after Evan was attacked. John cautiously stepped down the street and was aghast to find nobody around. “I knew it. I shouldn’t have come here.” But something interrupted his next sentence, “You want the money?” It was a man, John turned around and saw clothes as strange as his own, a cloak with a hood that covered the persons’ face. John stepped back and slowly nodded, “Y…Yes.” The man held up a bundle of bills, one hundreds this time, “I have more in my car, now give me the disk. It’s rightfully mine.” John was confused, “What disk? A computer disk?” The man nodded and almost yelled, “You know what I’m talking about.” When John shook his head the cloaked man put the money back in his pocket and snickered, “You have it…” With those words the man sprung forward and grabbed the collar of Johns’ trenchcoat. “I don’t… Let me go you crazy-“ John couldn’t finish his sentence, for he was pushed on the ground. Before he could get up he felt a hard boot in his side; it hit inbetween his middle ribs. That was all that was needed to weaken John, he was very weak already, and he needn’t get too roughed up. The man felt in Johns’ pockets and pantlegs, everything and cursed when he didn’t find what he wanted.<br>
<br>
Evan took off his coat when he got home to his apartment. He was tired and achy, the vomiting and the hit on his head actually sobered him up a little. He took a shower and fell right asleep. He would never go to Willies’ bathroom again. <br>
<br>
Still several weeks before all of this. Nathan had the cloak and hood over his face as he walked slowly up the street to the bank. He snapped black gloves on as he walked. He stepped rather quickly; windows on an armored car don’t break easily. The passenger door opened and an officer stepped out and looked around. The driver door opened and another officer stepped out. The passenger officer called, “I’m going to go on ahead, Jim. I got some of the money, you gonna be okay checking out here?” The officer named Jim answered, “Yeah, I got it. Go on ahead. I figured we should go to take the armored car to Green Wing.” Green Wing was another bank nearby. The passenger officer went towards the bank with a large bag of money. Jim kept the door open and went back inside the armored car. Nathan stepped quietly towards the car, but stopped when Jim closed the door. The passenger officer just stepped into the bank. Nathan took a deep breath, took off his cloak and tossed it on the ground, and stepped past the armored car. He looked at his wristwatch, good, it wasn’t closing time yet. The cop and Nathan were roughly the same size, they had the same type of hair also. Nathan walked through the big double doors, and started to go into the second set of smaller doors but stopped. The space between the lobby of the bank and outside was dark, if someone crouched up against the wall it would be hard to see them, unless you were really looking. Nathan looked through the small doors window and saw the police officer talking to what Nathan guessed was the manager of the bank. The manager smiled and shook the police officers hand, the officer turned and started toward the entrance door. Nathan held his breath and crouched against the sidewall, just as the door opened. The officer closed the door behind him , he held the empty money bag, Nathan took his chance. He covered the officers’ mouth with one of his hands and grabbed the combat knife out of the holster with the other.<br>
<br>
John woke up a few hours later, on the sidewalk in front of the library, a few moments after his attacker left he passed out. He sat up slowly and groggily and looked around, he saw the bundle of money, the man didn’t take it. John stuffed it into his coat pocket. There were a few things he had to buy to stash somewhere, then he’d go to his favorite place. John went the EZ Mart closeby and bought the bare essentials, lunch meat, a bottle of water, some bread, a deli sandwich. He stuffed them in his pocket. Then he stopped at the alley he was sleeping in before, there was a small grate in the wall near the floor with a cardboard box in it. John pulled the grate off and opened the box. Inside was a cigar, a pickle jar with a few quarters in it, and a photograph. The photograph showed a small boy, about eight years old, smiling at the camera. Behind the boy was a building. John smiled at the picture before putting the other things in the box. He put the lid on the box and set the grate over the hole. John then went to his ‘favorite’ place; Willies’ Bar and Grill. It was his favorite mostly because of the friendly bartender, Mack. <br>
<br>
Evan opened his eyes, he sighed when he saw it was still night. He was already sobered up, he didn’t seem to have a hangover either, how lucky.  He sat up in his bed and looked at the alarm clock. 1:20 AM. That’s it, he kept waking up like this, he decided to take a walk. As soon as he sat up the phone rang. He cursed under his breath and answered it, “H…Hello?” The voice was very familiar, cheery, something Evan rarely experienced. <br>
“Hi! Is this Evan?” Ira Emitenicham, a happy woman, two years younger than Evan, she looked and acted like she was even younger. Very long last name…<br>
“Oh, hi Ira. What’s up?” Evan rubbed the sleep from his eyes and got up from bed.<br>
“Nothing, I was just wonderin’, you wanna go out somewhere?” They never went ‘out’, as in a date, they were strictly friends. Evan joked about it though.<br>
“Are you asking me on a date?”<br>
“Noooo! Well, do you?”<br>
“Isn’t it pretty late? Or do you never sleep?”<br>
“Wha!? The night is young, friend. C’mon.” Evan smiled and turned the light on in his bedroom.<br>
“Sure, where should we meet?” Evan walked into the kitchen, he had a cordless phone.<br>
“Well duh! The Hole in the Wall.” Evan opened the refrigerator.<br>
“Willies? I just came from there, I got jumped.”<br>
“What? Really? Are you joking?”<br>
“Nope, it was some guy in a cloak, he was looking for a disk.”<br>
“How much did he take?”<br>
“None at all, it was weird.”<br>
“Oh… Well, I’ll protect you from dark strangers. Wussy boy.”<br>
“I was drunk, I would have roughed him up if I wasn’t.”<br>
“Yeah, yeah. Well, meet me there.”<br>
“ Wait, do you want me to take my car?”<br>
“No, walkings better for drunk people. It reduces the risk of an accident.” She snickered and they said goodbye.<br>
<br>
The security watched the monitors that showed the most dangerous criminals. There were two guards to watch the monitors. Each worked for about 12 hours each, at 12 midnight they switched, both waited in the lounge to drink their’ coffee for about seven minutes. Nobody would escape in seven minutes, or so it was suspected. Norman knew all of this from overhearing the new security guard and a police officer outside the door. Norman had excellent hearing. In the middle of the night as he lay in his cot, he held the pen under the blanket and thought with his eyes closed. The officer that walked in every now and then to give him food counted the pens in the hold each time he came in, just in case Norman decided to take one. Norman slowly unscrewed the pen from the middle, so slowly that you wouldn’t be able to tell that he was fidgeting at all. He found the inside of the pen, which was a thin tube with the ball tip at the end, inside the transparent tube was a coil which made the tip go up and down when you pressed the button at the end. Norman took the inside part of the pen and stuck it up his orange prison sleeve, then screwed the outside back together. He stretched and opened his eyes, just to look at the clock. 12:00 midnight, right on the dot. Norman waited until 12:01 and quickly got out of bed. He walked to the desk and put the outside of the pen in the holder, tip down so the guard wouldn’t see that it had no point. Norman didn’t want to take the risk to try escaping now, he would do it tomorrow. Norman sat up in his bed for a few minutes and went to sleep at 12: 06 midnight.<br>
<br>
Sam was getting worried, his parents had been in the hotel for ten minutes now. <br>
“I’ll wait a while longer, they’re probably signing up for some sweepstakes or something.” Sam spoke out in the car then tossed his drawing of the mountain in the backseat. He waited for several more minutes and opened the jeep door. Then he heard it, a rapid noise, like a very loud drum being repeadedly beat on. His heart beat wildly with the noise. It paused, and started up again. What was happening?<br>
<br>
Nathan thought as quickly as possible, if he slashed the officer, it would get blood all over the outfit. He had an idea, it would be rather crazy, but it would work. Nathan undid the officers’ shirt in a quick manner, like a bird pecking at worms. He took the shirt off, under it was a white tank top with his knife hand. The officer reached for his gun but Nathan kicked him in the back of the knee, making him crouch. He tightened his grip on the officers mouth then pulled his head so he looked at the ceiling. Then, in a very clean manner, he drove the blade into the mans’ neck and across it. He had to be quick, Nathan layed the dead officer down near the corner of the sidewall and undid the mans’ pants. “This is making me sick…” He whispered as he saw striped boxer shorts when he pulled the pants off. Nathan then proceeded to take the mans’ shoes, then the belt with the gun holster. Nathan took his trenchcoat off and stuffed it in the moneybag, he buttoned the cops shirt over his, then polished the badge. He pulled the officers’ pants over his own, they fit almost perfect, and then he took his belt off and put it in the bag along with the knife and holster. Blood was forming on the floor. He took his boots off and tossed them in the bag. Then put the officers shoes on, a little big, but not too bad. He took a few breaths, grabbed the moneybag, and stepped out into the night air.<br>
