<br>
<br>
John Cook ordered a drink from Mack, the place was dead, and nobody was there. The only lights were above the bar, they were like spotlights, it made the rest of the place dark. <br>
“Mack, you don’t know what it’s like.” Mack was cleaning a glass behind the bar.<br>
“What what’s like?”<br>
“Making a few mistakes, and living in regret.” John shook his head and gulped down some of the vodka.<br>
“Where’d you get the money?” Mack asked curiously, maybe trying to change Johns mind.<br>
“It’s a long story.” The bar door opened, and in stepped two younger people. A man and a woman. Maybe ten years younger than himself. The girl talked loudly and cheerfully, while the man was slightly quieter. John smiled; it was tender age in bloom was what it was. Thinking about just made him sadder, so he ordered a refill. <br>
<br>
Ira Emitenicham was young and fair looking. It was hard to say if she was pretty, she wasn’t close to ugly. It was confusing. She had blond straight hair that went down about half a foot below her shoulders. She wore braces that were visible, a slight green color is what she had on them. She had blue eyes that were very light but very… Strange. She didn’t have much opinion about herself. She was happy that Evan decided to go to Willies with her this late. She was getting lonely living alone in that god-forsaken house of hers.<br>
“So, a guy beat you up in a bathroom and he said he was looking for a disk?” Ira asked. Evan nodded and shrugged.<br>
“A computer disk?” <br>
“I don’t know.”<br>
“Hey Mack. We’d like… Um… Just a few beers, whatever you got.”<br>
Mack remembered Evan, <br>
“Back already?”<br>
Evan smiled.<br>
“I’m back for the hair of the dog that bit me.” <br>
Mack laughed and gave them the drinks. Ira sighed happily, Evan obviously heard it because he commented.<br>
“Are you a bimbo?” He asked.<br>
“What!? Who said that?”<br>
“Nobody, you are just so happy all the time.”<br>
Ira rolled her eyes, he didn’t know a thing.<br>
“I’m just grateful.”<br>
“Well, I’m envious.”<br>
They drank their drinks as Mack read the week befores’ newspaper. Ira noticed a rough looking guy on the other side of the bar. He wore very strange clothing, she giggled to Evan,<br>
“Look at that guy.” Evan saw him and replied,<br>
“He must be a hobo.”<br>
Mack called out from behind the newspaper, <br>
“Oh my god! That armored car that was missing was found next to an abandon highway. The money was missing, so was a computer disk-“ He was cut off by Evan and the scraggly man.<br>
“Disk?” <br>
Ira looked at the hobo and back to Evan, then back to the hobo. <br>
“Did you get attacked by a cloaked guy?” She asked.<br>
“Yeah, he wanted a disk, and I said I didn’t know what he was talking about. So he roughed me up, didn’t take nothin’.”<br>
Mack read out loud again.<br>
“What’s inside the disk is confidential, there was 100,000 dollars worth of money stolen. At the scene was one dead police officer, he was shot. In the passenger seat were police clothes. The dead police corpse at Cashman Bank is the one who was supposed to be with the dead officer in the car. Both death causes are expected to be done by the same person; there were absolutely no clues to who the killer and thief might be. Officials say that if this person gets access to what is on the disk, havoc will wreak.” There was a bated silence for a few moments. The scraggly man at the bar said out loud,<br>
“Someone else wants that disk, and it aint no cop. Cops don’t do that.” <br>
Evan nodded,<br>
“That’s for sure.”<br>
“Let’s get out of here.” Ira suggested, they went outside, it was getting chilly.<br>
“Where do you want to go?” Evan asked. Ira thought for a few moments and shrugged,<br>
“I don’t care, let’s go back to your place.” They did, and though they didn’t show it before, they were exhausted. Ira slept in Evans’ bed and Evan on the couch in the living room.<br>
<br>
A few moments after the two younger kids left, John went back the alleyway. He opened the grate and fit his body inside it. It wasn’t that dirty under the building, John had spread some blankets all over. He had a candle on a paint can with a single match next to it. John was grateful he was so skinny so he could fit in the hole. He put the grate back where it was, lit the match and the candle. He opened the ‘storage box’ and grabbed a few pieces of bread and put the rest of his money in the box, he still had quite a lot more bills. He ate the pieces of bread slowly and savored them each. When he was done he put out the candle, put the lid on the box and layed down in the shadows, on a dirty blanket, he was lulled to sleep by a bird chirping far off.<br>
<br>
About a week after his heist on the armored car, which went great, Nathan Freeman sat on his couch in his apartment. He put out his cigarette butte and sighed happily. He was still very happy about the huge success of the robbery. His prize was the best anyone could wish for. 100,000 dollars, and a floppy disk. The disk was the best part, when he first got home he immediately popped it in his computer. What came up on the screen made his eyes light up with excitement. But before he put it in he had to get it out of a steel box that was sealed shut. He cut it open with several seconds with his chainsaw on it. But what was on the disk amazed him. Codes, thousands, no, millions of them. At first he didn’t know what they were, but he figured it out. Government codes, top secret information about military weapons, status on most wanted people, and the best part, codes for the programming of those weapons. There was more, much more. He could do things you couldn’t imagine with this, he could almost control the USA, maybe the world! Some people wouldn’t see how, but a clever person like Nathan could see the possibilities, he didn’t know where to start. But when he came home from a ride around town, the disk was gone. It wasn’t in his computer, it wasn’t anywhere. He didn’t know who to look for, or where. But somehow, the disk installed information on his computer, it had several peoples’ names on it. It showed that they were looking for the disk with that information for years, it ranged from the age of 11 to 60 years old. Nathan smiled and decided to start with the first on the list, a young man by the name of Evan Teadows.<br>
<br>
Sam cried out in fright when he saw the glass in the hotel lobbys’ window shatter. He ducked down and could clearly hear what the drumming noise was: Gunfire. Sam locked the car doors and crawled into the backseat. He layed on the floor in the back and covered himself with a sheet that he used when taking a nap on the way to the hotel. He breathed heavily and winced when gunshots fired. He stayed in that position for hours, but when the gunshots stopped, he was asleep from sheer exhaustion, it was late, and his parents hadn’t come yet.<br>
<br>
The next morning, Norman awoke early and did his morning exercises. He sat at the desk, doing nothing until it was breakfast. He made sure that the tube was slid far up his sleeve. Harris, a security guard, came in with a tray of bacon and eggs and orange juice. He set it on the desk outside of the cell and said, “Good morning Norman. You’re up early, as usual. Regular procedure.” Norman nodded and smiled charmingly, he went up to the cell bars and turned his back to them. He sat down and slid his arms between the bars so they were behind him. Norman breathed normally as the handcuffs snapped around his wrists. Harris checked Normans’ hands to see if he had anything. “Here comes the food. Hungry, Norman?” Harris asked, Norman smiled, “Yes, quite hungry.” Harris laughed and grabbed his key ring from his belt, picked a key out, and unlocked the cell. He then put the ring on his belt and brought the tray in and set it on the drawing desk. Harris counted the pens, “One, two, three, four. Good. Well, See you at lunch, Norman.” Harris said as he locked the cell door. He unlocked Normans’ handcuffs and took them away.<br>
<br>
Evan woke up at eleven o’ clock the next morning. He rubbed his eyes and stretched, sat up, and went to the bathroom. He went to see if Ira was awake, she wasn’t. Evan crouched and dived up on the bed, making it bounce, Ira sat up with a snap, <br>
“I’m up!” Evan sat on the bed next to her,<br>
“Good morning.”<br>
“No.”<br>
“What?”<br>
“There were twelve marhsmellows. Then the carrot came.”<br>
“Wake up!” Evan yelled and Ira rubbed her eyes. <br>
“What time is it?” She asked.<br>
“About eleven.”<br>
<br>
Sams’ eyes opened with a snap, he smelt leather, and he heard people talking. He saw a brown leathery cushion a few inches in front of his face; it was a couch. The voices were clearer, <br>
“So, do you know the kids’ name yet?” The first voice asked.<br>
“No.” A second voice answered.<br>
“Should we wake him up and ask?”<br>
“Let’s let him sleep for a few more minutes.”<br>
He had a blanket over him. Sam tried to remember what happened, then a sinking feeling in his stomach came, and he sat up and looked around, two men in police outfits were at the door. One had a clipboard. The room looked like a waiting room. There was a water fountain on one side, a cofee table with magazines on it near the couch and the door. The men looked over and saw him up. One of them said in a cheerful tone, <br>
“Hey, sport! You’re up!” Sport? Sam didn’t like this guy too much already. The other officer rolled his eyes and walked out. Sam looked down at his clothes; they were the same as when he heard the noises. He blinked and asked, <br>
“Where are my parents?” The officer seemed to ignore him.<br>
“We’re going to need you to answer some questions for us.”<br>
“Where are my parents?”<br>
“Please answer honestly.” (is this a trial?)<br>
“Sir,”<br>
“Okay, now what is your full name.”<br>
“Sam John Biggins, now where is my mom and dad?” The officer flipped through some papers on his clipboard and looked up.<br>
“Now how old are you?” (interrogation? what happened?)<br>
“Eleven… Or twelve, what day is it?” The officer told him, it was the day after the noises, and he was twelve.<br>
“I’m twelve, where are my parents? Are they okay?”<br>
“Were you at the Gosfard Hotel &amp; Suites last night?”<br>
“Yes.” (might as well cooperate, darn idiot.)<br>
“Did you have parents with you?” (no, I’m just asking about parents I don’t have, moron.)<br>
“Yeah.” Sam sighed impatiently, “Can you tell me where they are?”<br>
“Did you witness anything?”<br>
“I heard gunshots, then the front window broke, then I ducked down under some covers in the jeep.”<br>
“What jeep?”<br>
“The family jeep.” (duh)<br>
“Now can you tell me your name again?”<br>
“Sam John Biggins.”<br>
The officer glanced through the clipboard and frowned.<br>
“Are your’ parents named Natalie Biggins and Forrest Biggins?”<br>
Oh no, Sam frowned also, he prayed nothing bad happened.<br>
“Yes.”<br>
The officer looked down at the ground and sighed (oh my god) and put his free hand over his face.<br>
“Sam… Your mother and father (please no no no!) were in the hotel when an armed madman shot in the lobby. Only a few people got out, the man didn’t do it for a reason (who cares why he did it! please oh please don’t let it be what I think.), but out of the bodies we found (……..).” The officer paused and closed his eyes, “Your’ parents were two of them (nononononoNONONONONONO! never never!).” Sam stared blankly ahead,<br>
“What?” (lying he’s lying is what it is, a lie a lie a lie! a joke!)<br>
“Your parents’ were murdered.” (YOU LIE YOU SCUM! YOU HORRIBLE, NASTY INSIFNIFIGANT PIECE OF MUD!)<br>
“No… You are lying…” Sam grabbed a magazine off the coffee table and opened it.<br>
“Sam, I’m sorry.”<br>
“You are a liar!” Sam closed the magazine and threw it across the room. “Where are they?”<br>
“In the… Morgue.”<br>
“QUIT LYING (ITS YOUR FAULT ALL YOUR FAULT)! JUST STOP IT! (I’M NOT COMIN’ BACK COMING BACK COMIN’ BACK!)”<br>
Sam threw the covers off of him and stood up, his shoes were gone. He ran around the coffee table and saw his shoes, he picked them up and ran out of the room. A few dozen people in doctor clothes rushed around, some had people following them, some were pushing a stretcher. Sam heard the door open behind him and the cheery bastards’ voice, <br>
“Sam, get back in here.”<br>
Sam broke into a dash, he dodged around the doctors and saw a desk with a black woman behind it, <br>
“Can I help you, son?” She asked in a calm voice.<br>
“Where’s the mourge?” Sam answered, Cheerful was coming his way.<br>
“Why?”<br>
“I have a friend seeing someone there.”<br>
“Down this hall,” She pointed to her left, “The third door on the right.”<br>
Cheerful was coming up, Sam went down the hallway and counted doors on the right side. He pushed the third door open and slammed it behind him, the glass on the window of it shook. Sam turned and locked it and looked around, it was a very dark room, Cheerful banged on the door,<br>
“Come on Sam! Just come out!”<br>
The only light came from spotlights that flashed on the ‘slabs’ as some people call it. Bodies were covered with blankets. (i’m not gonna find them here, just strangers.) Sam turned and closed the blinds on the window of the door that Cheerful and some doctors banged on. He turned around and lowered the blinds on the door. Then he walked around the dark room, examining the names near the covered corpses (covered corpses corpses covered hee heee hee.) and took a shaky breath when he saw Forrest Biggins near a covered body. The banging was becoming harder. Sam walked closer to (it’s not him, a mix up. A mistake.) to the body and raised his hand above the head. He saw some blood marks on the chest area, his eyes were watering. He lightly grabbed hold of the covers on the face and brought it down to about the collar bone area. <br>
“Dad… I’m sorry… I’m sorry we could never talk… I mean, talk the way I do with my mom. I love you.” Sam bent down and hugged his father, then put the covers over his face. The racket was hurting Sam’s ears, “Quit banging!” He said it so loud that it actually did stop. Cheerfuls voice came,<br>
“Sam, unlock the door Sam, we want to help.” Sam looked at the body next to Dads’ and read the name, Natalie Biggins. He saw blood marks around the same area as his dads’. Sam stared blankly at the sheet for several moments before he pulled the cover down to moms’ collarbone also. Her face was beautiful, Sam wiped his wet eyes. <br>
“Mom, I am so sorry. We could have been more of a real family, but I ruined it. You know, you like the Sleeping Beauty; do you remember that movie? I always wanted to watch it again and again.” He laughed a little and wiped his eyes. “Well, I wish that if I kissed you, you would wake up, but that won’t happen. Listen to me talking to a lifeless abode of organs and stuff. I know you’re not here, and I know that you are probably happy, up there in Summerland, or Heaven, or whatever it is. Do you guys promise to give me a tour when I get up there? O… Okay.” His tears were flowing a little more, he bent down and kissed his mom, on the cheek. The banging had started again, Sam heard a cop say,<br>
“The door is very tight, were gonna need to break it down.” A few moments later the glass shattered and the blinds swayed, the top part of a fire axe was sticking out of the window. The blinds went up, revealing Cheerfuls’ face, <br>
“Come on, Sam, this is crazy. Climb out this window and we’ll figure something out.”<br>
Sam absentmindedly reached into his pocket and pulled something out, it was a hat, it went over Sams’ head, with a patch on the front saying CABIN, and on the bottom was fluffy white stuff. Sam put it on and said to Cheerful in a demanding tone, “I want both of my parents cremated so they won’t keep going back to the body to see it, I want it within three days from now, Understand?” Cheerfuls’ expression was blank,<br>
“O…Okay, whatever you want, just unlock the door. I can’t reach it.” Sam looked around the room and smiled through his blotchy face at a window with shades over it. He opened the shades, light poured into the room, but before he left, he had one more thing to do.<br>
<br>
About two weeks after this, some trashcans tipping over awakened John. He opened his eyes quickly. He peeked through the grate and saw a pear of small sneakers poking from the mess of trashcans. He also saw someone running around the corner. The sneakers moved, John opened the grate and climbed out,<br>
“Is someone there?” He asked with caution, his heart was beating. A young voice answered,<br>
“Yeah…” There was some shuffling, the sneakers disappeared and the trashcans moved. To Johns’ tired surprise, and half expectation, the person who wore the sneakers was a young boy, about ten or eleven,<br>
“Hi.” The boy said shyly, he wore a dirty, ocean blue T-shirt with a big brown jacket over it. His pants were black and dirty also. He also had a strange hat, it looked somewhat Russian. The hat had a patch on the front that read CABIN. John was curious,<br>
“What happened?” The boy looked behind him and back to John,<br>
“Some guy with a black cape and hood stopped me some ways down the street. He asked about some sort of disk. I said I didn’t-“<br>
John interrupted him,<br>
“Wait! He asked for a disk?” The boy nodded. “And he was dressed like some kind of Batman?” The boy nodded again. “Well I’ll be damned. What’s yer’ name?”<br>
The kid answered, “Sam… Why?” John said to himself,<br>
“Let’s see here. Last night a bundle of money literally fell on my lap, I went to the location a piece of paper told me to to get more. Then a man in a dark cloak and hood attacked me because I didn’t have a certain ‘disk’ he wanted. I went to a bar that night and the bartender read a news article.” John told what the article said and continued, <br>
“Another man in that bar was attacked for a disk he didn’t have the same night. Now, the next morning, you get attacked for the same reason.” Sam stopped him,<br>
“Who said I was attacked?”<br>
“You were, weren’t you?”<br>
“Yes.”<br>
“This guy must really want that disk.”<br>
“Well duh!”<br>
“Wha?” Did this kid know something?<br>
“It has government codes on it.”<br>
“How ya’ figure?”<br>
“Why else would a guy look for it so desperately? There are even people who dedicate their’ lives to search for it. Now that this cloaked guy heard that it’s not under security, it would be easier to get. You think they’re gonna ship a video game in an armored car?”<br>
This kid wasn’t stupid; that was for sure.<br>
“How old are you anyways?”<br>
“Twelve.”<br>
“Where are your’ parents?”<br>
“In Summerland.”<br>
“Summerland?”<br>
“They’re dead. Summerland is another name for Heaven.”<br>
“Oh… Sorry.”<br>
“What’s your’ name?<br>
“John.”<br>
<br>
“Dammit! The kid didn’t have it either. Who’s next? Norman Peterman, status? Currently jailed? What’s this? How can he possibly have it? Next, Mack Gar. Good, I know exactly where he should be.”<br>
<br>
“Okay, it says here, attach Fun Filly Fubster Family Fair Roller Coaster Car on the tracks, but where on the tracks?” Evan asked as he looked at the picture on the instruction manual. Ira set the Fun Filly Fubster Family Fair Ferris Wheel to the side and tried attaching the Fun Filly Fubster Family Fair Roller Coaster Car to the tracks, which she finished earlier, <br>
“How the heck do you do this?” Evan shook his head<br>
“Disgusting, how is a 6 to 9 year old going to do this if we can’t? Ooh, look, they have a phone number.”<br>
“A phone number for a toy?” Ira replied, Evan laughed as he picked up the work phone. Ira worked for a small toy store in town, since the place wasn’t too famous, Evan and her played with most of the new ones they got. Someone answered, a lady.<br>
“Gracias, et tu at Fun Filly Fubste’ Family Fair play set.” The lady greeted.<br>
“Um… Hi, I wanted to ask about a part on the Fun Filly Fubster Family Fair.”<br>
“Juavos?”<br>
“What? No, it’s the Fun Filly Fubster Family Fair Roller Coaster Car, I can’t get it on the tracks.”<br>
“Oooooh, Kenikwa?”<br>
“Uh… You no hablo… Um….English?” <br>
“Abikawata! Konichiwa!” <br>
“Are you speaking a real language?”<br>
“Kapa!” <br>
“Poopie head.”<br>
“Kaa?”<br>
“Ka ka! Dookie.”<br>
The lady answered, her tone was different.<br>
“Hey man, have some respect.”<br>
“So you speak English?”<br>
Nobody answered, it was silence. “Hello?”<br>
Evan heard a snap and looked over to Ira, the Fun Filly Fubster Family Fair Roller Coaster Car (phew.) had broken. Ira threw it up in the air,<br>
“Ahh, screw it, nobody likes that stuff anyways.”<br>
“The phone’s dead… That or that lady hung up on me.”<br>
“Oh well, it’s my lunch break, let’s go see Mack.”<br>
Willies’ was only a few buildings away. Evan took a deep breath when he got inside, following Ira. It was dead, just like last night, but where was Mack? Ira called out,<br>
“Mack?” Mack answered from somewhere,<br>
“H…Hey, Ira… I’m behind the bar.”<br>
“Where?”<br>
“Down… Down here.” Ira bent over the bar and gasped, <br>
“Omigosh! What happened!?”<br>
Evan looked over the bar also, Mack was sitting on the ground, in his work clothes, he had bruises on his face, a cut on his eyebrow dripped blood.<br>
“Oh man.”<br>
<br>
“Dammit…” Norman whispered to himself, his plan with the pen wouldn’t work. His plan had been that when 12 midnight came, he would scream for help, when a guard came in, he would stab him with the tube, the ink would surely leak in and kill him. Then take the keys to the cell, but then he would have to get passed some of the hall guards, which would be easy, but that left the guard at the front desk. He would see him through one of the monitor and call the alarm. Police from other squadrons would be on him in no time. His other plan was to try and unlock the cell with a part from the pen; the lock was too big. Norman tapped his fingers on the drawing desk. Suddenly, he smiled, a plan. He could still use the pen tube. <br>
<br>
Nathan sighed, why didn’t any of these people have it? Then it hit him, Nathan hadn’t checked inside the houses of these people. Luckily, the disk loaded the address of the home and workplace of these people. With the exception of the bum, of course, and probably the prisoner. He looked at Evans’ address and closed the window. <br>
“It has to be in one of these peoples’ houses.” He said to himself as he walked downt he street. The sky was overcast, cloudy in most areas, but small patches of clear blue sky dotted the area. Nathan had written Evan’s address on a napkin.<br>
